# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: liquid-templating
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:liquid-templating/comparison-of-web-template-engines] The following table lists the various web template engines used in Web template systems and a brief rundown of their features.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] A **markup language** is a text-encoding system which specifies the structure and formatting of a document and potentially the relationships among its parts.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Markup can control the display of a document or enrich its content to facilitate automated processing.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] A markup language is a set of rules governing what markup information may be included in a document and how it is combined with the content of the document in a way to facilitate use by humans and computer programs.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The idea and terminology evolved from the marking up of paper manuscripts (e.g., with revision instructions by editors), traditionally written with a red pen or blue pencil on authors' manuscripts.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Older markup languages, which typically focus on typesetting and presentation, include troff, TeX, and LaTeX.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Scribe and most modern markup languages, such as XML, identify document components (for example headings, paragraphs, and tables), with the expectation that technology, such as stylesheets, will be used to apply formatting or other processing.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Some markup languages, such as the widely used HTML, have pre-defined presentation semantics, meaning that their specifications prescribe some aspects of how to present the structured data on particular media.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] HTML, like DocBook, Open eBook, JATS, and many others, are based on the markup metalanguages XML and SGML.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] That is, SGML and XML allow designers to specify particular schemas, which determine which elements, attributes, and other features are permitted, and where.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] A key characteristic of most markup languages is that they allow combining markup with content such as text and pictures.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] For example, if a few words in a sentence need to be emphasized, or identified as a proper name, defined term, or another special item, the markup may be inserted between the characters of the sentence.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The word *markup* is derived from the traditional publishing practice of *marking up* a manuscript, which involves adding handwritten annotations in the form of conventional symbolic printer's instructions—in the margins and text of a paper or printed manuscript.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] For centuries, this task was done primarily by skilled typographers known as *markup men* or *markers* who marked up text to indicate what typeface, style, and size should be applied to each part, and then passed the manuscript to others for typesetting by hand or machine.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The markup was also commonly applied by editors, proofreaders, publishers, and graphic designers, and by authors themselves, all of whom might also mark things such as corrections and changes.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] There are three general categories of electronic markup, articulated by James Coombs, Allen Renear, and Steven DeRose in 1987, and Tim Bray in 2003.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Presentational markup is used by traditional word-processing systems.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Binary codes embedded within document text produce the WYSIWYG ('what you see is what you get') effect.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Such markup is usually hidden from human users, even authors and editors.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Such systems use procedural and descriptive markup internally but convert them to present the user with formatted arrangements of type.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Markup is embedded in text which provides instructions for programs to process the text.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Well-known examples include troff, TeX, and Markdown.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Generally, software processes the text sequentially from beginning to end, following the instructions as encountered.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Such text is often edited with the markup visible and directly manipulated by the author.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Popular procedural markup systems usually include programming constructs, especially macros, allowing complex sets of instructions to be invoked by a simple name (and perhaps a few parameters).
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] This is much faster, less error-prone, and more maintenance-friendly than re-stating the same or similar instructions in many places.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Descriptive markup is specifically used to describe parts of the document for what they are, rather than how they should be processed.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Well-known systems that provide many such labels include LaTeX, HTML, and XML.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The objective is to decouple the structure of the document from any particular treatment or rendition of it.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Such markup is often described as *semantic*.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] An example of a descriptive markup is HTML's `<cite>` tag, which is used to label a citation.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Descriptive markup—sometimes called *logical markup* or *conceptual markup*—encourages authors to write in a way that describes the material conceptually, rather than visually.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] There is considerable overlap and concurrent use of markup types.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] In modern word-processing systems, presentational markup is often saved in descriptive-markup-oriented systems such as XML, and then processed procedurally by implementations.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The programming in procedural-markup systems, such as TeX, may be used to create higher-level markup systems that are more descriptive in nature, such as LaTeX.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] In recent years, several markup languages have been developed with ease of use as a key goal, and without input from standards organizations, aimed at allowing authors to create formatted text via web browsers, for example in wikis and web forums.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] These are sometimes called lightweight markup languages.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Markdown, BBCode, and the markup language used by Wikipedia are examples of such languages.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The first well-known public presentation of markup languages in computer text processing was made by William W.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Tunnicliffe at a conference in 1967, although he preferred to call it *generic coding.* It can be seen as a response to the emergence of processing programs such as RUNOFF that each used their own control notation, often specific to the target typesetting device.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] In the 1970s, Tunnicliffe led the development of a standard called GenCode for the publishing industry.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Book designer Stanley Rice published speculation along similar lines in 1970.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Brian Reid, in his 1980 dissertation at Carnegie Mellon University, developed a theory and working implementation of descriptive markup in actual use.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] However, IBM researcher Charles Goldfarb is more commonly considered the inventor of markup languages.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Goldfarb developed the basic idea while working on a primitive document management system intended for law firms in 1969, and helped invent IBM's Generalized Markup Language (GML) later that same year.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] GML was first publicly disclosed in 1973.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] In 1975, Goldfarb moved from Cambridge, Massachusetts to Silicon Valley and became a product planner at the IBM Almaden Research Center.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] There, he convinced IBM's executives to deploy GML commercially in 1978 as part of IBM's Document Composition Facility product, and it was widely used in business within a few years.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML), the first standard descriptive markup language, was based on both GML and GenCode.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] It was the result of an International Organization for Standardization (ISO) committee that was first chaired by Tunnicliffe, and which Goldfarb also worked on beginning in 1974.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Goldfarb eventually became chair of the committee.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] SGML was first released by ISO as the ISO 8879 standard in October 1986.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Some early examples of computer markup languages available outside the publishing industry can be found in typesetting tools on Unix systems such as troff and nroff.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] In these systems, formatting commands were inserted into the document text so that typesetting software could format the text according to the editor's specifications.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] It was a trial and error iterative process to correctly print a document.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The availability of WYSIWYG publishing software supplanted much use of these languages among casual users, though professional publishing work still uses markup to specify the non-visual structure of texts, and WYSIWYG editors now usually save documents in a markup-language-based format.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Another major publishing standard is TeX, created and refined by Donald Knuth in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] TeX concentrated on the detailed layout of text and font descriptions to typeset mathematical books.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] This required Knuth to spend considerable time investigating the art of typesetting.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] TeX is mainly used in academia, where it is a *de facto* standard in many scientific disciplines.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] A TeX macro package known as LaTeX provides a descriptive markup system on top of TeX, and is widely used both among the scientific community and the publishing industry.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The first language to make a clear distinction between structure and presentation was Scribe, developed by Brian Reid and described in his doctoral thesis in 1980.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Scribe was revolutionary in a number of ways, introducing the idea of styles separated from the marked-up document, and a grammar that controlled the usage of descriptive elements.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Scribe influenced the development of GML and later SGML, and is a direct ancestor to HTML and LaTeX.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] In the early 1980s, the idea that markup should focus on the structural aspects of a document and leave the visual presentation of that structure to the interpreter led to the creation of SGML.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The language was developed by a committee chaired by Goldfarb.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] It incorporated ideas from many different sources, including Tunnicliffe's project, GenCode.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Sharon Adler, Anders Berglund, and James A.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Marke were also key members of the SGML committee.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] SGML specifies a syntax for including the markup in documents, as well as one for separately describing what tags are allowed, and where (the document type definition (DTD), later known as a schema).
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] This allows authors to create and use any markup they want, selecting tags that make the most sense to them and are named in their own natural languages, while also allowing automated verification.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Thus, SGML is properly a metalanguage, and many markup languages are derived from it.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] From the late 1980s onward, most substantial new markup languages have been based on SGML, including the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) guidelines and DocBook.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] SGML was promulgated as the ISO 8879 standard in 1986.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] SGML found wide acceptance and use in fields with very large-scale documentation requirements.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] However, many found it cumbersome and difficult to learn—a side effect of its design attempting to do too much and being too flexible.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] For example, SGML made end tags (or start tags, or both) optional in certain contexts, because its developers thought markup would be done manually by overworked support staff who would appreciate saving keystrokes.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] In 1989, computer scientist Tim Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system, then specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by SGMLguid, an in-house SGML-based documentation format at CERN, and very similar to the sample schema in the SGML standard.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Berners-Lee considered HTML an SGML application.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formally defined it as such with the mid-1993 publication of the first proposal for an HTML specification: "Hypertext Markup Language (HTML)" by Berners-Lee and Dan Connolly, which included an SGML DTD to define the grammar.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] These formatting commands were derived from those used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Steven DeRose argues that HTML's use of descriptive markup (and the influence of SGML in particular) was a major factor in the success of the Web, because of the flexibility and extensibility that it enabled.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] HTML became the main markup language for creating web pages and other information that can be displayed in a web browser and is likely the most used markup language in the world in the 21st century.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] XML (Extensible Markup Language) is a widely used meta markup language.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] It was developed by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) in a committee created and chaired by Jon Bosak.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The main purpose of XML was to simplify SGML by focusing on a particular use case—documents on the Internet.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] XML remains a metalanguage like SGML, allowing users to create any tags needed (hence *extensible*) and then describing those tags and their permitted uses.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] XML adoption was hastened by the fact that every XML document can be written so that it is also an SGML document, allowing existing SGML users and software to switch to XML fairly easily.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] At the same time, XML eliminates many complex features of SGML to simplify implementation environments such as documents and publications.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] It appears to balance simplicity and flexibility, as well as support very robust schema definitions and validation tools, and was rapidly adopted for many uses.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] XML is now widely used for communicating data between applications, serializing program data, for hardware communication protocols, vector graphics, and other uses besides documents.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] From January 2000 until HTML 5 was released, all W3C recommendations for HTML were based on XML, using XHTML (Extensible HyperText Markup Language).
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The language specification requires that XHTML documents be *well-formed* XML documents.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] This allows for more rigorous and robust documents, by avoiding many syntax errors which historically led to unwanted browser behavior, while still using document components familiar to HTML users.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Another difference is that all attribute values in tags must be quoted.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Both these differences are commonly criticized as verbose but also praised because they make it far easier to detect, localize, and repair errors.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Finally, all tag and attribute names within the XHTML namespace must be lowercase to be valid.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] HTML, on the other hand, was case-insensitive.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Many XML-based applications exist, including the Resource Description Framework as RDF/XML, XForms, DocBook, SOAP, and the Web Ontology Language (OWL).
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] For a partial list of these, see list of XML markup languages.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] A common feature of many markup languages is that they intermix the text of a document with markup instructions in the same data stream or file.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] This is not necessary; it is possible to isolate markup from text content, using pointers, offsets, IDs, or other methods to coordinate the two.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Such *standoff* markup is typical for the internal representations that programs use to work with marked-up documents.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] However, *embedded* or *inline* markup is much more common elsewhere.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The codes enclosed in angle-brackets `<like this>` are markup instructions (known as *tags*), while the text between these instructions is the actual text of the document.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The codes `h1`, `p`, and `em` are examples of *semantic* markup, in that they describe the intended purpose or the meaning of the text they include.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Specifically, `h1` means the enclosed text is a *first-level heading*, `p` means a *paragraph*, and `em` means an *emphasized* word or phrase.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] A program interpreting such structural markup may apply its own rules or styles for presenting the various pieces of text, using different typefaces, boldness, font size, indentation, color, or other styles, as desired.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] For example, a tag such as `h1` might be presented in a large bold sans-serif typeface in an article, or it might be underscored in a monospaced (fixed-width font) document, or it might not change the presentation at all.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] In contrast, the `i` tag in HTML 4 is an example of *presentational* markup, which is generally used to specify a characteristic of the text without specifying the reason for that appearance.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] In this case, the `i` element dictates the use of an italic typeface.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] However, in HTML 5, this element has been repurposed with a more semantic usage: to denote "a span of text in an alternate voice or mood, or otherwise offset from the normal prose in a manner indicating a different quality of text".
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] For example, it is appropriate to use the `i` element to indicate a taxonomic designation or a phrase in another language.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The change was made to ease the transition from HTML 4 to 5 as smoothly as possible so that deprecated uses of presentational elements would preserve the most likely intended meaning.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] TEI has published extensive guidelines for how to encode texts of interest in the humanities and social sciences, developed through years of international cooperative work.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] These guidelines are used for encoding historical documents, and the works of particular scholars, periods, and genres.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] While the idea of markup language originated with text documents, they are increasingly used in the presentation of other types of information, including playlists, vector graphics, web services, content syndication, and user interfaces.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] Most of these are XML applications because XML is a well-defined and extensible language.
[src:liquid-templating/markup-language] The use of XML has also led to the possibility of combining multiple markup languages into a single profile, like XHTML+SMIL and XHTML+MathML+SVG.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting is often used to provide a customized interface for the user.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] These scripts may assemble client characteristics for use in customizing the response based on those characteristics, the user's requirements, access rights, etc.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting also enables the website owner to hide the source code that generates the interface, whereas, with client-side scripting, the user has access to all the code received by the client.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] A downside to the use of server-side scripting is that the client needs to make further requests over the network to the server in order to show new information to the user via the web browser.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] These requests can slow down the experience for the user, place more load on the server, and prevent the use of the application when the user is disconnected from the server.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example, according to the HTTP or FTP protocols, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both of those protocols).
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol, that can only be used with one another.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be considered client-side operations.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Netscape introduced an implementation of JavaScript for server-side scripting with Netscape Enterprise Server, first released in December, 1994 (soon after releasing JavaScript for browsers).
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting was later used in early 1996 by Fred Dufresne while developing the first website for Boston, MA television station WCVB.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] The technology is described in US patent 5835712 Archived 2020-02-25 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] The patent was issued in 1998 and is now owned by Open Invention Network (OIN).
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] In 2010, OIN named Fred DuFresne a "Distinguished Inventor" for his work on server-side scripting.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] In the earlier days of the web, server-side scripting was almost exclusively performed by using a combination of C programs, Perl scripts, and shell scripts using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI).
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Those scripts were executed by the operating system, and the results were served back by the web server.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Many modern web servers can directly execute on-line scripting languages such as ASP, JSP, Perl, PHP and Ruby either by the web server itself or via extension modules (e.g. mod_perl or mod_php) to the webserver.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] For example, WebDNA includes its own embedded database system.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Either form of scripting (i.e., CGI or direct execution) can be used to build up complex multi-page sites, but direct execution usually results in less overhead because of the lower number of calls to external interpreters.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Dynamic websites sometimes use custom web application servers, such as Glassfish, Plack and Python's "Base HTTP Server" library, although some may not consider this to be server-side scripting.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] When using dynamic web-based scripting techniques, developers must have a keen understanding of the logical, temporal, and physical separation between the client and the server.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] For a user's action to trigger the execution of server-side code, for example, a developer working with classic ASP must explicitly cause the user's browser to make a request back to the webserver.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripts are completely processed by the servers instead of clients.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] When clients request a page containing server-side scripts, the application server processes the scripts and returns an HTML page to the client.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] With the advent of single-page applications, an updated approach to server-side scripting was introduced, known as server-side rendering.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, static HTML can be sent from the server to the client, and client-side JavaScript then makes the web page dynamic by attaching event handlers to the HTML elements in a process called hydration.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Examples of frameworks that support server-side rendering are Next.js, Nuxt.js, Angular.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] An alternative to server-side rendering is static site generation.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, the page is generally assembled on the server once per each request.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] By contrast, with static site generation, the application generates all the static HTML pages at build time.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] These pre-built pages are then sent to the client at each request, without having to build them again.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] This leads to faster rendering times, since a new page doesn't have to be generated on every request; the server simply hands over a file it already generated in the past.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] The downside is that when some data on the page changes, it needs to be rebuilt.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Examples of static site generation tools are Jekyll and Gatsby.
[src:liquid-templating/server-side-scripting] Sites generated by static site generation tools are often hosted on Netlify, Vercel or GitHub pages.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] A **template processor** (also known as a **template engine** or **template parser**) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] The language that the templates are written in is known as a **template language** or **templating language**.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] For purposes of this article, a result document is any kind of formatted output, including documents, web pages, or source code (in source code generation), either in whole or in fragments.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] A template engine is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework, and may be used also as a preprocessor or filter.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] Template engines typically include features common to most high-level programming languages, with an emphasis on features for processing plain text.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] The templating languages are generally simple substitution-only languages, in contrast to the more sophisticated facilities in full-blown template processors, but may contain some logic.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] Simple examples include ‘printf’ print format strings, found in many programming languages, and snippets, found in a number of text editors and source code editors.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] In word processors, templates are a common feature, while automatic filling in of the templates is often referred to as mail merge.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] An illustrative example of the complementary nature of parsing and templating is the `s` (substitute) command in the sed text processor, originating from search-and-replace in the ed text editor.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] For example, `s/(cat|dog)s?/\1s/g` replaces all occurrences of "cat" or "dog" with "cats" or "dogs", without duplicating an existing "s": `(cat|dog)` is the 1st (and only) sub-expression in the regexp, and `\1` in the format string substitutes this into the output.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] This may be a relational database, a source file such as XML, an alternate format of flat file database, a spreadsheet or any of other various sources of preformatted data.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] Some template processing systems are limited in the types of data that can be used.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] Others are designed for maximum flexibility and allow many different types of data.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] Additionally some template engines allow additional configuration options.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] These may consist of an entire document or a document fragment.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] Template processing is used in various contexts for different purposes.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] The specific purpose is ordinarily contingent upon the software application or template engine in use.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] However, the flexibility of template processing systems often enables unconventional uses for purposes not originally intended by the original designers.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] A **template engine** is a specific kind of template processing module that exhibits all of the major features of a modern programming language.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] The term *template engine* evolved as a generalized description of programming languages whose primary or exclusive purpose was to process templates and data to output text.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] The use of this term is most notably applied to web development using a web template system, and it is also applied to other contexts as well.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] Document generation frameworks typically use template processing as the central model for generating documents.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] A web template engine processes web templates and source data (typically from a relational database) to produce one or more output web pages or page fragments.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] It is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] Currently, template processing software is most frequently used in the context of development for the web.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] XSLT is a template processing model designed by W3C.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] It is designed primarily for transformations on XML data (into web documents or other output).
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] Programming languages such as Perl, Python, PHP, Ruby, C#, Java, and Go support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] JavaServer Pages, Active Server Pages, Genshi (for Python), and eRuby are examples of template engines designed specifically for web application development.
[src:liquid-templating/template-processor] Moreover, template processing is sometimes included as a sub-feature of software packages like text editors, IDEs and relational database management systems.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] A **web template system** in web publishing allows web designers and developers to work with *web templates* to automatically generate custom web pages, such as the results from a search.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] This reuses static web page elements while defining dynamic elements based on web request parameters.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Web templates support static content, providing basic structure and appearance.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Developers can implement templates from content management systems, web application frameworks, and HTML editors.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] The template and content resources are processed and combined by the template engine to mass-produce web documents, each with a similar visual format.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, web documents include any of various output formats for transmission over the web via HTTP, HTTPS, or another Internet protocol.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] A template processor (also known as a template engine or template parser) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] The language that the templates are written in is known as a template language or templating language.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] With the model typically held in a relational database, the remaining components of the MVC architecture are the control and view.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] In the simplest of systems these two are not separated.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] However, adapting the separation of concerns principle one can completely decouple the relationships.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] A web browser and web server are a client–server architecture.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Sites often also use a web cache to improve performance.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] In many implementations, template files contain variables or placeholders that are replaced with data supplied by an application when the page is generated.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] The source code of the template engine can be proprietary or open source.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Many template systems are a component of a larger programming platform or framework.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] They are referred to as the "platform's template system".
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Some template systems have the option of substituting a different template language or engine.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Programming languages such as Perl, Ruby, C, and Java support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] JavaServer Pages (JSP), PHP, and Active Server Pages (ASP with VBScript, JScript or other languages) are examples, themselves, of web template engines.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] These technologies are typically used in server-side templating systems, but could be adapted for use on an "edge-side" proxy or for static page generation.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Static site generators are engines that use flat text input files like markdown and asciidoc to generate a static web page.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Examples of this include Jekyll (Liquid, Ruby), Hugo (Go templates), and Pelican (Jinja2, Python).
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Some hosted website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, provide template-based systems that allow users to create static and dynamic web pages through graphical user interfaces rather than traditional programming.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] HTML editors often use web template systems to produce only static web pages.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] These can be viewed as a ready-made web design, used to mass-produce "cookie-cutter" websites for rapid deployment.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] They also commonly include themes in place of CSS styles.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] In general, the template language is used only with the editor's software.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] FrontPage and Dreamweaver were once the most popular editors with template sub-systems.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] A Flash web template uses Macromedia Flash to create visually interactive sites.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Many *server-side template systems* have an option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] This is common on content management systems, like Vignette, but is not considered out-server generation.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] In the majority of cases, this "publish option" doesn't interfere with the *template system*, and it can be made by external software, as Wget.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existent software adapted for this task.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for the web use, running on CGI.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, started with SSI.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Technically, the methodology of embedding programming languages within HTML (or XML, etc.), used in many "server-side included script languages" are also templates.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] All of them are Embedded complex languages.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] There are also preprocessors used as server-side template engines.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] As for edge-side template and inclusion systems, "edge-side" refers to web servers that reside in the space between the client (browser) and the originating server.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] They are often referred to as "reverse-proxy" servers.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] These servers are generally tasked with reducing the load and traffic on originating servers by caching content such as images and page fragments, and delivering this to the browser in an efficient manner.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Basic Edge Side Includes (ESI) is an SSI-like language.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] ESI has been implemented for content delivery networks.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] The ESI template language may also be implemented in web browsers using JavaScript and Ajax, or via a browser "plug-in".
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] Many web browsers can apply an XSLT stylesheet to XML data that transforms the data into an XHTML document, thereby providing template functionality in the browser itself.
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] The most simple form is transclusions (HTML frames).
[src:liquid-templating/web-template-system] In other cases dynamic web pages are needed.
